      <div xml:id="NA237-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi uraimāṟupaṭṭatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante is inimical in word.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA237">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            naṉimikap pacantu tōḷuñ cāayp</l>
<l>            paṉimali kaṇṇum paṇṭu pōlā</l>
<l>            viṉṉuyi raṉṉa pirivaruṅ kātalar</l>
<l>            nīttu nīṭiṉa reṉṉum pulavi</l>
<l>            yuṭkoṇ ṭūṭiṉṟu milaiyō maṭantai </l>
<l>            yuvakkāṇ ṭōṉṟuva vōṅki viyappuṭai</l>
<l>            yiravalar varūu maḷavai yaṇṭiraṉ</l>
<l>            puravetirntu tokutta yāṉai pōla</l>
<l>            vulaka muvappa vōtarum</l>
<l>            vēṟuppal luruvi ṉērtaru maḻaiyē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The vexation that says:</l>
<l rend="indent3">“[our] lover from whom separation is difficult</l>
<l rend="indent3">as from [our] sweet life has left [and] prolonged [his absence],</l>
<l rend="indent4">[our] shoulder, very much faded<note place="foot">Actually we would expect <term xml:lang="ta">pacanta</term>, the <term xml:lang="ta">pey</term>. here.</note>, becoming emaciated,</l>
<l rend="indent4">[our] eyes abounding in dew unlike [they were] formerly,”</l>
<l>didn’t you take it to heart and pick a quarrel at all<note place="foot">For the type of negation where the perfective neuter singular in -<term xml:lang="ta">aṉṟu</term> has to be analysed as an verbal noun see note on NA 27.</note>, girl?</l>
<l>See these<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">uva</term> can well be read as the n.pl. of <term xml:lang="ta">utu</term>, and there are contexts, as T.V.G. affirms, where it is used in this more specific sense.</note>: there appear clouds that rise</l>
<l rend="indent">in many different forms, difficult to count(?)<note place="foot">Is this the implication of <term xml:lang="ta">ōtu</term> here, usually "to recite, to study" (a word rather from the poetological idiom than from the poetry itself)?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent2">for the world to rejoice, just like the elephants</l>
<l rend="indent3">gathered, when facing a grant<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">puravu etir</term>: this phrase is unclear, and T.V.G. renders it by "when granting protection" (which might in the end refer to the same thing).</note>, by Aṇṭiraṉ at the time</l>
<l rend="indent4">the beggars are coming [to him] in high amazement.<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains that <term xml:lang="ta">Aṇṭiraṉ</term> is a different name of <term xml:lang="ta">Āy</term>, one of the seven liberal chiefs specially remembered by tradition (enumerated in the <term xml:lang="ta">Ciṟupāṇāṟṟupaṭai</term>) who had the habit of presenting solicitors with elephants as a present.</note></l>
    </lg>
      </div>
